DORA Compliance Playbook | EU Regulation 2022/2554
Prepared by: Melissa Rilauven
For use in B2B tenders: Financial entities & ICT third-party service providers

1. ICT Risk Management | Art. 5–16
Governance: Management body bears ultimate responsibility for ICT risk. Must define, approve, oversee ICT risk management framework and allocate adequate budget/resources.
Framework Requirements: Implement continuous ICT risk management process: identification, protection & prevention, detection, response & recovery. Align with ISO 27001/NIST CSF. Conduct risk assessments at least annually and before major changes.
Key Controls: Asset inventory, encryption of data at rest/in transit, access control/privileged access management, patch & vulnerability management, business continuity & disaster recovery plans.
2. ICT Incident Management & Reporting | Art. 17–23
Incident Classification: Classify incidents as “major” based on: # of clients/financial counterparts affected, downtime, data losses, reputational impact, economic impact. Use ESAs template.
Reporting Timeline: Initial notification within 4 hours from classification of major incident. Intermediate report within 72 hours. Final report within 1 month after root cause analysis. Report to competent authority + CSIRTs.
Process: Establish and implement ICT-related incident management process to detect, manage, notify incidents. Maintain records of all incidents, including near-misses.
3. Digital Operational Resilience Testing | Art. 24–27
Annual Testing: Financial entities must test all critical ICT systems at least annually via vulnerability scans, network security assessments, penetration testing.
TLPT Requirement: Threat-Led Penetration Testing (TLPT) every 3 years for entities identified as significant by authorities. Must use external testers, follow TIBER-EU framework.
Remediation: Document test results, address vulnerabilities, retest. Management body must review results.
4. Third-Party ICT Risk Management | Art. 28–44
Register of Information: Maintain up-to-date register of all contractual arrangements with ICT third-party providers, including subcontractors. Submit to authority annually.
Key Contractual Clauses: Contracts must include: full service descriptions, locations of data processing, audit & access rights for entity/authority, security requirements, exit strategies, incident reporting obligations.
Oversight: Cannot outsource responsibility. Must assess concentration risk, perform due diligence before contracting, monitor provider performance and risk continuously. Critical providers may be subject to direct EU oversight.
5. Information Sharing | Art. 45
Threat Intelligence: Financial entities may exchange cyber threat information and intelligence within trusted communities to enhance collective resilience.
Requirement: Sharing must protect sensitive data, comply with GDPR, and occur via secure arrangements. Voluntary but encouraged by regulators.
