DORA Compliance Playbook | EU Regulation 2022/2554
Prepared by: Melissa Rilauven
Scope: Financial Entities & ICT Third-Party Service Providers | Date: April 2026

1. ICT Risk Management Framework | Articles 5–16
Regulatory Requirement: Establish and maintain a sound, comprehensive ICT risk management framework as part of overall risk management system.

Key Implementation Points:

Governance & Accountability: The management body defines risk appetite, approves ICT strategy, and is ultimately responsible for ICT risk. Appoint ICT risk control function with direct reporting line.
Risk Identification: Maintain complete, classified inventory of all ICT assets, business functions, and supporting processes. Map dependencies on ICT third-party providers.
Protection & Prevention: Implement security policies based on ISO 27001/NIST CSF. Mandatory controls: access management & MFA, cryptography for data at rest/in transit, vulnerability & patch management with defined SLAs, network security, data backup & restoration.
Detection: Continuous monitoring capabilities for anomalous activities. Deploy SIEM/SOC services proportionate to risk profile.
Response & Recovery: Documented ICT Business Continuity Policy & Response/Recovery Plans. Plans must include communication strategies, alternative processing sites, and be tested annually.
Review Cycle: Conduct ICT risk assessments at least annually, after major ICT incidents, and before deployment of new critical systems.
2. ICT-Related Incident Management & Reporting | Articles 17–23
Regulatory Requirement: Detect, manage, and classify ICT-related incidents. Report major incidents to competent authority.

Key Implementation Points:

Incident Definition: Any event compromising availability, authenticity, integrity or confidentiality of data/systems. Includes cyber-attacks, ICT system failures.
Classification Criteria: An incident is “major” if it meets thresholds across: clients/counterparts affected, downtime, data losses, reputational impact, economic cost, geographical spread. ESAs provide common templates.
Reporting Deadlines:
Initial notification: Within 4 hours of classifying incident as major.
Intermediate report: Within 72 hours with updated impact assessment.
Final report: Within 1 month including root cause analysis and remediation plan.
Internal Process: Establish early warning indicators, escalation procedures, and communication protocols for clients and authorities. Maintain log of all incidents, including non-major and near-misses.
3. Digital Operational Resilience Testing | Articles 24–27
Regulatory Requirement: Establish testing program to assess preparedness and identify weaknesses in ICT systems.

Key Implementation Points:

Baseline Testing: Conduct annual testing of all critical ICT systems. Includes vulnerability assessments, open source analysis, network security assessments, scenario-based tests, penetration testing, and compatibility testing.
Advanced Testing – TLPT: Entities designated by authorities must conduct Threat-Led Penetration Testing every 3 years. Must follow TIBER-EU framework, use qualified external testers, and simulate tactics of real threat actors.
Governance: Management body must approve testing plan, allocate resources, and review results. All vulnerabilities must be remediated with validation testing.
Scope: Testing covers not only production systems but also backups, recovery procedures, and physical security of data centers.
4. Managing ICT Third-Party Risk | Articles 28–44
Regulatory Requirement: Manage risks from ICT third-party providers across entire lifecycle. Ultimate responsibility cannot be outsourced.

Key Implementation Points:

Strategy & Policy: Adopt ICT third-party risk strategy aligned with business strategy. Include concentration risk assessment.
Register of Information: Maintain detailed, up-to-date register of all contractual arrangements with ICT providers, including all subcontractors in critical functions. Submit annually to competent authority.
Due Diligence: Perform risk assessment before contracting. Assess provider’s security, financial stability, substitutability, and location risk.
Contractual Requirements: Contracts must contain: complete service descriptions, data processing/storage locations, full audit & access rights for entity & authorities, security/encryption standards, incident reporting obligations, exit strategies to ensure continuity, and compliance with EU data rules.
Ongoing Monitoring: Continuously monitor provider performance, security posture, and compliance. Right to conduct on-site audits.
Critical Providers: Providers designated as “critical” by ESAs are subject to direct Union oversight framework.
5. Information Sharing Arrangements | Article 45
Regulatory Requirement: Financial entities may exchange cyber threat information to enhance collective resilience.
Key Implementation Points:
Scope: Share indicators of compromise, tactics, techniques, procedures, and cyber threat intelligence.
Conditions: Must be within trusted communities, protect commercially sensitive data, ensure GDPR compliance, and use secure channels.
Benefit: Participation demonstrates proactive security posture and is viewed favorably by regulators, though voluntary.
